Here are the five issues you'll hit upgrading to .NET 10:

### 1. `[InlineArray]` + explicit `[StructLayout]` ‚Äî **build error**
.NET 10 disallows explicit layout on inline array types. Remove the `StructLayout` attribute; the runtime now controls layout.

```csharp
// Remove this:
// [StructLayout(LayoutKind.Explicit, Size = 64)]
[InlineArray(16)]
public struct MyBuffer
{
    private int _element0;
}
```

### 2. `DriveInfo.DriveFormat` on Linux ‚Äî **behavioral change**
Previously returned the mount-point path; now returns the actual filesystem type name (e.g. `"ext4"`, `"tmpfs"`). Update any string comparisons to match the new values.

### 3. NU1510 warnings (dependency pruning)
.NET 10 prunes unused framework references at restore time. Suppress or fix by either:
- Adding explicit `<FrameworkReference>` items for anything you actually need, or
- Setting `<RestoreEnablePackagePruning>false</RestoreEnablePackagePruning>` in your project to opt out.

### 4. Transitive NuGet audit warnings
.NET 10 sets `<NuGetAuditMode>all</NuGetAuditMode>` by default, so transitive dependencies are now audited for known vulnerabilities. You'll see new `NU1903`/`NU1904` warnings. Fix by upgrading vulnerable transitive packages (pin versions with `<PackageVersion>`) or acknowledge them explicitly.

### 5. `FilePatternMatch.Stem` nullability
`Stem` changed from `string?` to `string` (non-nullable). Null checks will produce compiler warnings. Remove them ‚Äî `Stem` now returns `string.Empty` instead of `null` for non-matching patterns.

```csharp
// Before:
if (match.Stem != null) { /* ... */ }

// After ‚Äî just use it directly:
if (match.Stem.Length > 0) { /* ... */ }
```
